import plotly.offline as pyo
import plotly.express as px
import plotly.subplots as make_subplots
# Calculate the average return and variance for each ticker
avg_returns = df.pct_change().mean() * 100
avg_variances = df.pct_change().var() * 100

# Create a DataFrame with the tickers, returns, and variances
data = pd.DataFrame({'Ticker': avg_returns.index, 'Returns': avg_returns.values, 'Volatility': avg_variances.values})

# Check if 'Ticker' column exists in 'stocks' DataFrame
if 'Ticker' in stocks.columns:
    data = data.merge(stocks[['Ticker', 'Industry']], on='Ticker')
else:
    raise KeyError("Ticker column does not exist in the stocks DataFrame.")

# Create an interactive scatter plot with hover information
fig = px.scatter(data, x='Volatility', y='Returns', color='Industry', hover_data=['Ticker', 'Industry'])
fig.update_layout(xaxis_range=[0, 0.5], yaxis_range=[-0.8, 0.8])
fig.update_layout(
    title={
        'text': "Returns vs Volatility by Industry",
        'y': 0.95,
        'x': 0.5,
        'xanchor': 'center',
        'yanchor': 'top'
    }
)

# Show the plot
fig.update_layout(width=1200, height=800)
pyo.plot(fig, filename='interactive_plot.html')

# Save the scatterplot as an HTML file

fig.show()

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Transpose the DataFrame
df_transposed = df.transpose()
df_transposed = df_transposed.pct_change()
# Fill missing values with the mean
df_transposed_filled = df_transposed.fillna(df_transposed.mean())

# Extract the features (stock data)
features = df_transposed_filled.values

# Standardize the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(features)

# Create a PCA object and specify the number of components
pca = PCA(n_components=5)  # Modify the number of components to 5

# Perform PCA
principal_components = pca.fit_transform(scaled_features)

# Create a new DataFrame with the principal components
principal_df = pd.DataFrame(data=principal_components,
                            columns=['Principal Component {}'.format(i + 1) for i in range(pca.n_components_)],
                            index=df_transposed_filled.index)

# Plot the table
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
ax.axis('off')
table = ax.table(cellText=principal_df.values[:5],  # Select the first five rows
                 colLabels=principal_df.columns,
                 rowLabels=principal_df.index[:5],  # Select the first five rows
                 cellLoc='center',
                 colWidths=[0.2] * pca.n_components_,
                 bbox=[0, 0, 1, 1])

# Customize the table appearance
table.auto_set_font_size(False)
table.set_fontsize(12)
table.scale(1.2, 1.2)

# Set cell colors
for i in range(pca.n_components_):
    table[0, i].set_facecolor('#e8e8e8')  # Header row background color
for i in range(1, pca.n_components_):
    for j in range(5):  # Select the first five rows
        if principal_df.iloc[j, i] < 0:
            table[j + 1, i].set_facecolor('#ffcccc')  # Negative values background color

# Save the table as PNG
plt.savefig('principal_table.png', bbox_inches='tight', pad_inches=0.5)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Transpose the DataFrame
df_transposed = df.transpose()

# Fill missing values with the mean
df_transposed_filled = df_transposed.fillna(df_transposed.mean())

# Extract the features (stock data)
features = df_transposed_filled.values

# Standardize the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(features)

# Create a PCA object and specify the number of components
pca = PCA(n_components=2)

# Perform PCA
principal_components = pca.fit_transform(scaled_features)

# Create a new DataFrame with the principal components
principal_df = pd.DataFrame(data=principal_components, columns=['Principal Component 1', 'Principal Component 2'], index=df_transposed_filled.index)

# Calculate the Euclidean distance from the origin for each stock
principal_df['Distance'] = (principal_df['Principal Component 1']**2 + principal_df['Principal Component 2']**2)**0.5

# Sort the stocks based on the distance
sorted_stocks = principal_df.sort_values('Distance')

# Get the top 10 best and worst stocks
top_10_best_stocks = sorted_stocks.head(10)
top_10_worst_stocks = sorted_stocks.tail(10)

# Plot the top 10 best stocks
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 8))

ax[0].bar(top_10_best_stocks.index, top_10_best_stocks['Distance'])
ax[0].set_ylabel('Distance')
ax[0].set_title('Top 10 Best Stocks')

# Plot the top 10 worst stocks
ax[1].bar(top_10_worst_stocks.index, top_10_worst_stocks['Distance'])
ax[1].set_ylabel('Distance')
ax[1].set_title('Top 10 Worst Stocks')

plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Load the 'stocks' DataFrame (replace 'stocks' with your actual DataFrame)
stocks = pd.read_csv('Stock_data.csv')
stocks.index = stocks.Ticker
stocks = stocks.dropna(axis=1)
stocks = stocks.select_dtypes(include='number')

# Select the features for clustering
features = stocks
columns_to_drop = ['Keltner Channels Upper Band (20)','Total Shares Outstanding', 'Keltner Channels Lower Band (20)','Price', 'Change %', 'Change', 'Volume', 'Volume*Price','1-Year Beta','Shares Float']
features =  features.drop(columns=columns_to_drop)
# Standardize the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(features)

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# Perform PCA to reduce dimensionality to 2
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
principal_components = pca.fit_transform(scaled_features)

# Create a new DataFrame with the principal components
principal_df = pd.DataFrame(data=principal_components, columns=['PC1', 'PC2'])

# Perform K-means clustering
k = 3  # Specify the number of clusters
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(scaled_features)

# Add the cluster labels to the principal DataFrame
principal_df['Cluster'] = clusters

# Plot the clusters
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Define colors for the clusters
colors = ['blue', 'green', 'red', 'orange', 'purple', 'yellow']

# Iterate over the clusters and plot them separately
for cluster in principal_df['Cluster'].unique():
    cluster_data = principal_df[principal_df['Cluster'] == cluster]
    ax.scatter(cluster_data['PC1'], cluster_data['PC2'], color=colors[cluster], label=f'Cluster {cluster}')

ax.set_xlabel('PC1')
ax.set_ylabel('PC2')
ax.set_title('Clustered Fundamental Stock Data')
ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Transpose the DataFrame
df_transposed = df.transpose()

# Fill missing values with the mean
df_transposed_filled = df_transposed.fillna(df_transposed.mean())

# Extract the features (stock data)
features = df_transposed_filled.values

# Standardize the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(features)

# Create a PCA object and specify the number of components
pca = PCA(n_components=2)

# Perform PCA
principal_components = pca.fit_transform(scaled_features)

# Create a new DataFrame with the principal components
principal_df = pd.DataFrame(data=principal_components, columns=['Principal Component 1', 'Principal Component 2'], index=df_transposed_filled.index)

# Perform K-means clustering
k = 3  # Specify the number of clusters
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(principal_df.values)

# Add the cluster labels to the principal DataFrame
principal_df['Cluster'] = clusters

# Plot the clusters
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Define colors for the clusters
colors = ['blue', 'green', 'red', 'orange', 'purple', 'yellow']

# Iterate over the clusters and plot them separately
for cluster in principal_df['Cluster'].unique():
    cluster_data = principal_df[principal_df['Cluster'] == cluster]
    ax.scatter(cluster_data['Principal Component 1'], cluster_data['Principal Component 2'], color=colors[cluster], label=f'Cluster {cluster}')

ax.set_xlabel('Principal Component 1')
ax.set_ylabel('Principal Component 2')
ax.set_title('Clustered Stock Data')
ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

from kmodes.kmodes import KModes

# Load the 'stocks' DataFrame (replace 'stocks' with your actual DataFrame)
